[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] In statistics and, in particular, in the fitting of linear or logistic regression models, the **elastic net** is a regularized regression method that linearly combines the *L*1 and *L*2 penalties of the lasso and ridge methods.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] Nevertheless, elastic net regularization is typically more accurate than both methods with regard to reconstruction.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] Use of this penalty function has several limitations.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] For example, in the "large *p*, small *n*" case (high-dimensional data with few examples), the LASSO selects at most *n* variables before it saturates.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] Also if there is a group of highly correlated variables, then the LASSO tends to select one variable from a group and ignore the others.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] To overcome these limitations, the elastic net adds a quadratic part ( $\|\beta \|^{2}$ ) to the penalty, which when used alone is ridge regression (known also as Tikhonov regularization).
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] The quadratic penalty term makes the loss function strongly convex, and it therefore has a unique minimum.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] The elastic net method includes the LASSO and ridge regression: in other words, each of them is a special case where $\lambda _{1}=\lambda ,\lambda _{2}=0$ or $\lambda _{1}=0,\lambda _{2}=\lambda$ .
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] Meanwhile, the naive version of elastic net method finds an estimator in a two-stage procedure : first for each fixed $\lambda _{2}$ it finds the ridge regression coefficients, and then does a LASSO type shrinkage.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] This kind of estimation incurs a double amount of shrinkage, which leads to increased bias and poor predictions.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] To improve the prediction performance, sometimes the coefficients of the naive version of elastic net is rescaled by multiplying the estimated coefficients by $(1+\lambda _{2})$ .
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] It was proven in 2014 that the elastic net can be reduced to the linear support vector machine.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] A similar reduction was previously proven for the LASSO in 2014.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] The authors showed that for every instance of the elastic net, an artificial binary classification problem can be constructed such that the hyper-plane solution of a linear support vector machine (SVM) is identical to the solution $\beta$ (after re-scaling).
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] The reduction immediately enables the use of highly optimized SVM solvers for elastic net problems.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] It also enables the use of GPU acceleration, which is often already used for large-scale SVM solvers.
[src:elastic-net/elastic-net-regularization] When $2p>n$ it is typically faster to solve the linear SVM in the primal, whereas otherwise the dual formulation is faster.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] In machine learning, **feature selection** is the process of selecting a subset of relevant features (variables, predictors) for use in model construction.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The central premise when using feature selection is that data sometimes contains features that are *redundant* or *irrelevant*, and can thus be removed without incurring much loss of information.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Redundancy and irrelevance are two distinct notions, since one relevant feature may be redundant in the presence of another relevant feature with which it is strongly correlated.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Feature extraction creates new features from functions of the original features, whereas feature selection finds a subset of the features.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Feature selection techniques are often used in domains where there are many features and comparatively few samples (data points).
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] A feature selection algorithm can be seen as the combination of a search technique for proposing new feature subsets, along with an evaluation measure which scores the different feature subsets.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The simplest algorithm is to test each possible subset of features finding the one which minimizes the error rate.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] This is an exhaustive search of the space, and is computationally intractable for all but the smallest of feature sets.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The choice of evaluation metric heavily influences the algorithm, and it is these evaluation metrics which distinguish between the three main categories of feature selection algorithms: wrappers, filters and embedded methods.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] In traditional regression analysis, the most popular form of feature selection is stepwise regression, which is a wrapper technique.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] It is a greedy algorithm that adds the best feature (or deletes the worst feature) at each round.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The main control issue is deciding when to stop the algorithm.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] In machine learning, this is typically done by cross-validation.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] In statistics, some criteria are optimized.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] This leads to the inherent problem of nesting.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] More robust methods have been explored, such as branch and bound and piecewise linear network.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Subset selection evaluates a subset of features as a group for suitability.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Subset selection algorithms can be broken up into wrappers, filters, and embedded methods.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Wrappers use a search algorithm to search through the space of possible features and evaluate each subset by running a model on the subset.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Wrappers can be computationally expensive and have a risk of over fitting to the model.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Filters are similar to wrappers in the search approach, but instead of evaluating against a model, a simpler filter is evaluated.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Embedded techniques are embedded in, and specific to, a model.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Many popular search approaches use greedy hill climbing, which iteratively evaluates a candidate subset of features, then modifies the subset and evaluates if the new subset is an improvement over the old.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Evaluation of the subsets requires a scoring metric that grades a subset of features.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Exhaustive search is generally impractical, so at some implementor (or operator) defined stopping point, the subset of features with the highest score discovered up to that point is selected as the satisfactory feature subset.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The stopping criterion varies by algorithm; possible criteria include: a subset score exceeds a threshold, a program's maximum allowed run time has been surpassed, etc.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Alternative search-based techniques are based on targeted projection pursuit which finds low-dimensional projections of the data that score highly: the features that have the largest projections in the lower-dimensional space are then selected.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] These scores are computed between a candidate feature (or set of features) and the desired output category.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] There are, however, true metrics that are a simple function of the mutual information; see here.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The choice of optimality criteria is difficult as there are multiple objectives in a feature selection task.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Many common criteria incorporate a measure of accuracy, penalised by the number of features selected.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Examples include Akaike information criterion (AIC) and Mallows's *Cp*, which have a penalty of 2 for each added feature.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] AIC is based on information theory, and is effectively derived via the maximum entropy principle.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] A maximum entropy rate criterion may also be used to select the most relevant subset of features.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Filter feature selection is a specific case of a more general paradigm called structure learning.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Feature selection finds the relevant feature set for a specific target variable whereas structure learning finds the relationships between all the variables, usually by expressing these relationships as a graph.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The most common structure learning algorithms assume the data is generated by a Bayesian Network, and so the structure is a directed graphical model.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The optimal solution to the filter feature selection problem is the Markov blanket of the target node, and in a Bayesian Network, there is a unique Markov Blanket for each node.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] There are different Feature Selection mechanisms around that utilize mutual information for scoring the different features.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The simplest approach uses the mutual information as the "derived" score.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] However, there are different approaches, that try to reduce the redundancy between features.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Peng *et al.* proposed a feature selection method that can use either mutual information, correlation, or distance/similarity scores to select features.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The aim is to penalise a feature's relevancy by its redundancy in the presence of the other selected features.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Suppose that there are n full-set features.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Let *xi* be the set membership indicator function for feature *fi*, so that *xi*=1 indicates presence and *xi*=0 indicates absence of the feature *fi* in the globally optimal feature set.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The mRMR algorithm is an approximation of the theoretically optimal maximum-dependency feature selection algorithm that maximizes the mutual information between the joint distribution of the selected features and the classification variable.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] As mRMR approximates the combinatorial estimation problem with a series of much smaller problems, each of which only involves two variables, it thus uses pairwise joint probabilities which are more robust.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] In certain situations the algorithm may underestimate the usefulness of features as it has no way to measure interactions between features which can increase relevancy.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] This can lead to poor performance when the features are individually useless, but are useful when combined (a pathological case is found when the class is a parity function of the features).
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Overall the algorithm is more efficient (in terms of the amount of data required) than the theoretically optimal max-dependency selection, yet produces a feature set with little pairwise redundancy.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] mRMR is an instance of a large class of filter methods which trade off between relevancy and redundancy in different ways.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] mRMR is a typical example of an incremental greedy strategy for feature selection: once a feature has been selected, it cannot be deselected at a later stage.
