[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] QPFS is solved via quadratic programming.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] It is recently shown that QFPS is biased towards features with smaller entropy, due to its placement of the feature self redundancy term $I(f_{i};f_{i})$ on the diagonal of H.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] An advantage of SPECCMI is that it can be solved simply via finding the dominant eigenvector of Q, thus is very scalable.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] SPECCMI also handles second-order feature interaction.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] In a study of different scores Brown et al. recommended the joint mutual information as a good score for feature selection.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The score tries to find the feature, that adds the most new information to the already selected features, in order to avoid redundancy.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The score uses the conditional mutual information and the mutual information to estimate the redundancy between the already selected features ( $f_{j}\in S$ ) and the feature under investigation ( $f_{i}$ ).
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] For high-dimensional and small sample data (e.g., dimensionality > 105 and the number of samples < 103), the Hilbert-Schmidt Independence Criterion Lasso (HSIC Lasso) is useful.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] HSIC always takes a non-negative value, and is zero if and only if two random variables are statistically independent when a universal reproducing kernel such as the Gaussian kernel is used.
