[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The optimization problem is a Lasso problem, and thus it can be efficiently solved with a state-of-the-art Lasso solver such as the dual augmented Lagrangian method.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The correlation feature selection (CFS) measure evaluates subsets of features on the basis of the following hypothesis: "Good feature subsets contain features highly correlated with the classification, yet uncorrelated to each other".
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Here, ${\overline {r_{cf}}}$ is the average value of all feature-classification correlations, and ${\overline {r_{ff}}}$ is the average value of all feature-feature correlations.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The $r_{cf_{i}}$ and $r_{f_{i}f_{j}}$ variables are referred to as correlations, but are not necessarily Pearson's correlation coefficient or Spearman's ρ.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Hall's dissertation uses neither of these, but uses three different measures of relatedness, minimum description length (MDL), symmetrical uncertainty, and relief.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The combinatorial problems above are, in fact, mixed 0–1 linear programming problems that can be solved by using branch-and-bound algorithms.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The features from a decision tree or a tree ensemble are shown to be redundant.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] A recent method called regularized tree can be used for feature subset selection.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Regularized trees penalize using a variable similar to the variables selected at previous tree nodes for splitting the current node.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Regularized trees only need build one tree model (or one tree ensemble model) and thus are computationally efficient.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Regularized trees naturally handle numerical and categorical features, interactions and nonlinearities.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] They are invariant to attribute scales (units) and insensitive to outliers, and thus, require little data preprocessing such as normalization.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Regularized random forest (RRF) is one type of regularized trees.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The guided RRF is an enhanced RRF which is guided by the importance scores from an ordinary random forest.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] A metaheuristic is a general description of an algorithm dedicated to solve difficult (typically NP-hard problem) optimization problems for which there is no classical solving methods.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Generally, a metaheuristic is a stochastic algorithm tending to reach a global optimum.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] There are many metaheuristics, from a simple local search to a complex global search algorithm.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The feature selection methods are typically presented in three classes based on how they combine the selection algorithm and the model building.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Filter type methods select variables regardless of the model.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] They are based only on general features like the correlation with the variable to predict.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Filter methods suppress the least interesting variables.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] The other variables will be part of a classification or a regression model used to classify or to predict data.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] These methods are particularly effective in computation time and robust to overfitting.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Filter methods tend to select redundant variables when they do not consider the relationships between variables.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] However, more elaborate features try to minimize this problem by removing variables highly correlated to each other, such as the Fast Correlation Based Filter (FCBF) algorithm.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Wrapper methods evaluate subsets of variables which allows, unlike filter approaches, to detect the possible interactions amongst variables.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Embedded methods have been recently proposed that try to combine the advantages of both previous methods.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] A learning algorithm takes advantage of its own variable selection process and performs feature selection and classification simultaneously, such as the FRMT algorithm.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] This is a survey of the application of feature selection metaheuristics lately used in the literature.
[src:elastic-net/feature-selection] Some learning algorithms perform feature selection as part of their overall operation.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The lasso method assumes that the coefficients of the linear model are sparse, meaning that few of them are non-zero.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] It was originally introduced in geophysics, and later by Robert Tibshirani, who coined the term.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso was originally formulated for linear regression models.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] This simple case reveals a substantial amount about the estimator.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] These include its relationship to ridge regression and best subset selection and the connections between lasso coefficient estimates and so-called soft thresholding.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] It also reveals that (like standard linear regression) the coefficient estimates do not need to be unique if covariates are collinear.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Though originally defined for linear regression, lasso regularization is easily extended to other statistical models including generalized linear models, generalized estimating equations, proportional hazards models, and M-estimators.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso's ability to perform subset selection relies on the form of the constraint and has a variety of interpretations including in terms of geometry, Bayesian statistics and convex analysis.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The LASSO is closely related to basis pursuit denoising.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso was introduced in order to improve the prediction accuracy and interpretability of regression models.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] It selects a reduced set of the known covariates for use in a model.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso was developed independently in geophysics literature in 1986, based on prior work that used the $\ell ^{1}$ penalty for both fitting and penalization of the coefficients.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Statistician Robert Tibshirani independently rediscovered and popularized it in 1996, based on Breiman's nonnegative garrote.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Prior to lasso, the most widely used method for choosing covariates was stepwise selection.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] That approach only improves prediction accuracy in certain cases, such as when only a few covariates have a strong relationship with the outcome.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] However, in other cases, it can increase prediction error.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] At the time, ridge regression was the most popular technique for improving prediction accuracy.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Ridge regression improves prediction error by shrinking the sum of the squares of the regression coefficients to be less than a fixed value in order to reduce overfitting, but it does not perform covariate selection and therefore does not help to make the model more interpretable.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso achieves both of these goals by forcing the sum of the absolute value of the regression coefficients to be less than a fixed value, which forces certain coefficients to zero, excluding them from impacting prediction.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] This idea is similar to ridge regression, which also shrinks the size of the coefficients; however, ridge regression does not set coefficients to zero (and, thus, does not perform variable selection).
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Consider a sample consisting of *N* cases, each of which consists of *p* covariates and a single outcome.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Here $\beta _{0}$ is the constant coefficient, $\beta :=(\beta _{1},\beta _{2},\ldots ,\beta _{p})$ is the coefficient vector, and t is a prespecified free parameter that determines the degree of regularization.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Additionally, the covariates are typically standardized ${\textstyle {\bigl (}\sum _{i=1}^{N}x_{i}^{2}=1{\bigr )}}$ so that the solution does not depend on the measurement scale.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Some basic properties of the lasso estimator can now be considered.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Ridge regression shrinks all coefficients by a uniform factor of $\ (1+N\lambda )^{-1}\$ and does not set any coefficients to zero.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Therefore, the lasso estimates share features of both ridge and best subset selection regression since they both shrink the magnitude of all the coefficients, like ridge regression and set some of them to zero, as in the best subset selection case.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Additionally, while ridge regression scales all of the coefficients by a constant factor, lasso instead translates the coefficients towards zero by a constant value and sets them to zero if they reach it.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In one special case two covariates, say *j* and *k*, are identical for each observation, so that $x_{(j)}=x_{(k)}$ , where $x_{(j),i}=x_{(k),i}$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Then the values of $\beta _{j}$ and $\beta _{k}$ that minimize the lasso objective function are not uniquely determined.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Several variants of the lasso, including the Elastic net regularization, have been designed to address this shortcoming.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso regularization can be extended to other objective functions such as those for generalized linear models, generalized estimating equations, proportional hazards models, and M-estimators.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso can set coefficients to zero, while the superficially similar ridge regression cannot.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] This is due to the difference in the shape of their constraint boundaries.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The lasso can be rescaled so that it becomes easy to anticipate and influence the degree of shrinkage associated with a given value of $\lambda$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] It is assumed that X is standardized with z-scores and that y is centered (zero mean).
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Let $\beta _{0}$ represent the hypothesized regression coefficients and let $b_{\text{OLS}}$ refer to the data-optimized ordinary least squares solutions.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] We can then define the Lagrangian as a tradeoff between the in-sample accuracy of the data-optimized solutions and the simplicity of sticking to the hypothesized values.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The first fraction represents relative accuracy, the second fraction relative simplicity, and $\lambda$ balances between the two.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Given a single regressor, relative simplicity can be defined by specifying $q_{i}$ as $|b_{\text{OLS}}-\beta _{0}|$ , which is the maximum amount of deviation from $\beta _{0}$ when $\lambda =0$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The hypothesized value of $\beta _{0}=0$ is selected if $\lambda$ is bigger than $R^{2}$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Furthermore, if $R^{2}=1$ , then $\lambda$ represents the proportional influence of $\beta _{0}=0$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In other words, $\lambda \times 100\%$ measures in percentage terms the minimal amount of influence of the hypothesized value relative to the data-optimized OLS solution.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Given multiple regressors, the moment that a parameter is activated (i.e. allowed to deviate from $\beta _{0}$ ) is also determined by a regressor's contribution to $R^{2}$ accuracy.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] First, $R^{2}=1-{\frac {(y-Xb)'(y-Xb)}{(y-X\beta _{0})'(y-X\beta _{0})}}.$ An $R^{2}$ of 75% means that in-sample accuracy improves by 75% if the unrestricted OLS solutions are used instead of the hypothesized $\beta _{0}$ values.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] If $b=b_{\text{OLS}}$ when $R^{2}$ is computed, then the diagonal elements of $R^{\otimes }$ sum to $R^{2}$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The diagonal $R^{\otimes }$ values may be smaller than 0 or, less often, larger than 1.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] If regressors are uncorrelated, then the $i^{th}$ diagonal element of $R^{\otimes }$ simply corresponds to the $r^{2}$ value between $x_{i}$ and y .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] A rescaled version of the adaptive lasso of can be obtained by setting $q_{{\mbox{adaptive lasso}},i}=|b_{{\text{OLS}},i}-\beta _{0,i}|$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] If regressors are uncorrelated, the moment that the $i^{th}$ parameter is activated is given by the $i^{th}$ diagonal element of $R^{\otimes }$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Even when regressors are correlated, the first time that a regression parameter is activated occurs when $\lambda$ is equal to the highest diagonal element of $R^{\otimes }$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] These results can be compared to a rescaled version of the lasso by defining $q_{{\mbox{lasso}},i}={\frac {1}{p}}\sum _{l}|b_{{\text{OLS}},l}-\beta _{0,l}|$ , which is the average absolute deviation of $b_{\text{OLS}}$ from $\beta _{0}$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] For $p=1$ , the moment of activation is again given by ${\tilde {\lambda }}_{{\text{lasso}},i}=R^{2}$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] If $\beta _{0}$ is a vector of zeros and a subset of $p_{B}$ relevant parameters are equally responsible for a perfect fit of $R^{2}=1$ , then this subset is activated at a $\lambda$ value of ${\frac {1}{p}}$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In other words, the inclusion of irrelevant regressors delays the moment that relevant regressors are activated by this rescaled lasso.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The adaptive lasso and the lasso are special cases of a '1ASTc' estimator.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The latter only groups parameters together if the absolute correlation among regressors is larger than a user-specified value.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Just as ridge regression can be interpreted as linear regression for which the coefficients have been assigned normal prior distributions, lasso can be interpreted as linear regression for which the coefficients have Laplace prior distributions.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The Laplace distribution is sharply peaked at zero (its first derivative is discontinuous at zero) and it concentrates its probability mass closer to zero than does the normal distribution.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] This provides an alternative explanation of why lasso tends to set some coefficients to zero, while ridge regression does not.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso can also be viewed as a convex relaxation of the best subset selection regression problem, which is to find the subset of $\leq k$ covariates that results in the smallest value of the objective function for some fixed $k\leq n$ , where n is the total number of covariates.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso variants have been created in order to remedy limitations of the original technique and to make the method more useful for particular problems.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Almost all of these focus on respecting or exploiting dependencies among the covariates.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Elastic net regularization adds an additional ridge regression-like penalty that improves performance when the number of predictors is larger than the sample size, allows the method to select strongly correlated variables together, and improves overall prediction accuracy.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Group lasso allows groups of related covariates to be selected as a single unit, which can be useful in settings where it does not make sense to include some covariates without others.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Further extensions of group lasso perform variable selection within individual groups (sparse group lasso) and allow overlap between groups (overlap group lasso).
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Fused lasso can account for the spatial or temporal characteristics of a problem, resulting in estimates that better match system structure.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso-regularized models can be fit using techniques including subgradient methods, least-angle regression (LARS), and proximal gradient methods.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Determining the optimal value for the regularization parameter is an important part of ensuring that the model performs well; it is typically chosen using cross-validation.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In 2005, Zou and Hastie introduced the elastic net.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] When *p* > *n* (the number of covariates is greater than the sample size) lasso can select only *n* covariates (even when more are associated with the outcome) and it tends to select one covariate from any set of highly correlated covariates.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Additionally, even when *n* > *p*, ridge regression tends to perform better given strongly correlated covariates.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] So the result of the elastic net penalty is a combination of the effects of the lasso and ridge penalties.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Returning to the general case, the fact that the penalty function is now strictly convex means that if $x_{(j)}=x_{(k)}$ , ${\hat {\beta }}_{j}={\hat {\beta }}_{k}$ , which is a change from lasso.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Therefore, highly correlated covariates tend to have similar regression coefficients, with the degree of similarity depending on both $\|y\|_{1}$ and $\lambda _{2}$ , which is different from lasso.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] This phenomenon, in which strongly correlated covariates have similar regression coefficients, is referred to as the grouping effect.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Grouping is desirable since, in applications such as tying genes to a disease, finding all the associated covariates is preferable, rather than selecting one from each set of correlated covariates, as lasso often does.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In addition, selecting only one from each group typically results in increased prediction error, since the model is less robust (which is why ridge regression often outperforms lasso).
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In 2006, Yuan and Lin introduced the group lasso to allow predefined groups of covariates to jointly be selected into or out of a model.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] This is useful in many settings, perhaps most obviously when a categorical variable is coded as a collection of binary covariates.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In this case, group lasso can ensure that all the variables encoding the categorical covariate are included or excluded together.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Another setting in which grouping is natural is in biological studies.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Since genes and proteins often lie in known pathways, which pathways are related to an outcome may be more significant than whether individual genes are.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Additionally, the penalty term is now a sum over $\ell ^{2}$ norms defined by the positive definite matrices $K_{j}$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] If each covariate is in its own group and $K_{j}=I$ , then this reduces to the standard lasso, while if there is only a single group and $K_{1}=I$ , it reduces to ridge regression.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Since the penalty reduces to an $\ell ^{2}$ norm on the subspaces defined by each group, it cannot select out only some of the covariates from a group, just as ridge regression cannot.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] However, because the penalty is the sum over the different subspace norms, as in the standard lasso, the constraint has some non-differential points, which correspond to some subspaces being identically zero.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Therefore, it can set the coefficient vectors corresponding to some subspaces to zero, while only shrinking others.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] However, it is possible to extend the group lasso to the so-called sparse group lasso, which can select individual covariates within a group, by adding an additional $\ell ^{1}$ penalty to each group subspace.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Another extension, group lasso with overlap allows covariates to be shared across groups, e.g., if a gene were to occur in two pathways.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The "gglasso" package by in R, allows for fast and efficient implementation of Group LASSO.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In some cases, the phenomenon under study may have important spatial or temporal structure that must be considered during analysis, such as time series or image-based data.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In 2005, Tibshirani and colleagues introduced the fused lasso to extend the use of lasso to this type of data.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The first constraint is the lasso constraint, while the second directly penalizes large changes with respect to the temporal or spatial structure, which forces the coefficients to vary smoothly to reflect the system's underlying logic.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Clustered lasso is a generalization of fused lasso that identifies and groups relevant covariates based on their effects (coefficients).
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The basic idea is to penalize the differences between the coefficients so that nonzero ones cluster.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In contrast, variables can be clustered into highly correlated groups, and then a single representative covariate can be extracted from each cluster.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Algorithms exist that solve the fused lasso problem, and some generalizations of it.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Algorithms can solve it exactly in a finite number of operations.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Lasso, elastic net, group and fused lasso construct the penalty functions from the $\ell ^{1}$ and $\ell ^{2}$ norms (with weights, if necessary).
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The bridge regression utilises general $\ell ^{p}$ norms ( $p\geq 1$ ) and quasinorms ( $0<p<1$ ).
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] It is claimed that the fractional quasi-norms $\ell ^{p}$ ( $0<p<1$ ) provide more meaningful results in data analysis both theoretically and empirically.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The non-convexity of these quasi-norms complicates the optimization problem.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The efficient algorithm for minimization is based on piece-wise quadratic approximation of subquadratic growth (PQSQ).
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The adaptive lasso was introduced by Zou in 2006 for linear regression and by Zhang and Lu in 2007 for proportional hazards regression.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The prior lasso was introduced for generalized linear models by Jiang et al. in 2016 to incorporate prior information, such as the importance of certain covariates.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In prior lasso, such information is summarized into pseudo responses (called prior responses) ${\hat {y}}^{\mathrm {p} }$ and then an additional criterion function is added to the usual objective function with a lasso penalty.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] the usual lasso objective function with the responses y being replaced by a weighted average of the observed responses and the prior responses ${\tilde {y}}=(y+\eta {\hat {y}}^{\mathrm {p} })/(1+\eta )$ (called the adjusted response values by the prior information).
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In prior lasso, the parameter $\eta$ is called a balancing parameter, in that it balances the relative importance of the data and the prior information.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] In the extreme case of $\eta =0$ , prior lasso is reduced to lasso.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] If $\eta =\infty$ , prior lasso will solely rely on the prior information to fit the model.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Furthermore, the balancing parameter $\eta$ has another appealing interpretation: it controls the variance of $\beta$ in its prior distribution from a Bayesian viewpoint.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Prior lasso is more efficient in parameter estimation and prediction (with a smaller estimation error and prediction error) when the prior information is of high quality, and is robust to the low quality prior information with a good choice of the balancing parameter $\eta$ .
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] This can be especially useful when the data is high-dimensional.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The procedure involves running lasso on each of several random subsets of the data and collating the results.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The loss function of the lasso is not differentiable, but a wide variety of techniques from convex analysis and optimization theory have been developed to compute the solutions path of the lasso.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] These include coordinate descent, subgradient methods, least-angle regression (LARS), and proximal gradient methods.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Subgradient methods are the natural generalization of traditional methods such as gradient descent and stochastic gradient descent to the case in which the objective function is not differentiable at all points.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] LARS is a method that is closely tied to lasso models, and in many cases allows them to be fit efficiently, though it may not perform well in all circumstances.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Proximal methods have become popular because of their flexibility and performance and are an area of active research.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The choice of method will depend on the particular lasso variant, the data and the available resources.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] However, proximal methods generally perform well.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The "glmnet" package in R, where "glm" is a reference to "generalized linear models" and "net" refers to the "net" from "elastic net" provides an extremely efficient way to implement LASSO and some of its variants.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The "celer" package in Python provides a highly efficient solver for the Lasso problem, often outperforming traditional solvers like scikit-learn by up to 100 times in certain scenarios, particularly with high-dimensional datasets.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] This package leverages dual extrapolation techniques to achieve its performance gains.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The celer package is available at GitHub.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Choosing the regularization parameter ( $\lambda$ ) is a fundamental part of lasso.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] A good value is essential to the performance of lasso since it controls the strength of shrinkage and variable selection, which, in moderation can improve both prediction accuracy and interpretability.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] However, if the regularization becomes too strong, important variables may be omitted and coefficients may be shrunk excessively, which can harm both predictive capacity and inferencing.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Cross-validation is often used to find the regularization parameter.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Information criteria such as the Bayesian information criterion (BIC) and the Akaike information criterion (AIC) might be preferable to cross-validation, because they are faster to compute and their performance is less volatile in small samples.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] An information criterion selects the estimator's regularization parameter by maximizing a model's in-sample accuracy while penalizing its effective number of parameters/degrees of freedom.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] Zou et al. proposed to measure the effective degrees of freedom by counting the number of parameters that deviate from zero.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] The degrees of freedom approach was considered flawed by Kaufman and Rosset and Janson et al., because a model's degrees of freedom might increase even when it is penalized harder by the regularization parameter.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] As an alternative, the relative simplicity measure defined above can be used to count the effective number of parameters.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] For the lasso, this measure is given by ${\hat {\mathcal {P}}}=\sum _{i=1}^{p}{\frac {|\beta _{i}-\beta _{0,i}|}{{\frac {1}{p}}\sum _{l}|b_{{\text{OLS}},l}-\beta _{0,l}|}},$ which monotonically increases from zero to p as the regularization parameter decreases from $\infty$ to zero.
[src:elastic-net/lasso-statistics] LASSO has been applied in economics and finance, and was found to improve prediction and to select sometimes neglected variables, for example in corporate bankruptcy prediction literature, or high growth firms prediction.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The most common form of regression analysis is linear regression, in which one finds the line (or a more complex linear combination) that most closely fits the data according to a specific mathematical criterion.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For example, the method of ordinary least squares computes the unique line (or hyperplane) that minimizes the sum of squared differences between the true data and that line (or hyperplane).
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For specific mathematical reasons (see linear regression), this allows the researcher to estimate the conditional expectation (or population average value) of the dependent variable when the independent variables take on a given set of values.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Less common forms of regression use slightly different procedures to estimate alternative location parameters (e.g., quantile regression or Necessary Condition Analysis) or estimate the conditional expectation across a broader collection of non-linear models (e.g., nonparametric regression).
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Regression analysis is primarily used for two conceptually distinct purposes.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] First, regression analysis is widely used for prediction and forecasting, where its use has substantial overlap with the field of machine learning.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Second, in some situations regression analysis can be used to infer causal relationships between the independent and dependent variables.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Importantly, regressions by themselves only reveal relationships between a dependent variable and a collection of independent variables in a fixed dataset.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] To use regressions for prediction or to infer causal relationships, respectively, a researcher must carefully justify why existing relationships have predictive power for a new context or why a relationship between two variables has a causal interpretation.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The latter is especially important when researchers hope to estimate causal relationships using observational data.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] He also distinguished between two inhomogeneous sets of data and might have thought of an *optimal* solution in terms of bias, though not in terms of effectiveness." He previously used an averaging method in his 1671 work on Newton's rings, which was unprecedented at the time.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The method of least squares was published by Legendre in 1805, and by Gauss in 1809.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Legendre and Gauss both applied the method to the problem of determining, from astronomical observations, the orbits of bodies about the Sun (mostly comets, but also later the then newly discovered minor planets).
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Gauss published a further development of the theory of least squares in 1821, including a version of the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The term "regression" was coined by Francis Galton in the 19th century to describe a biological phenomenon.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The phenomenon was that the heights of descendants of tall ancestors tend to regress down towards a normal average (a phenomenon also known as regression toward the mean).
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For Galton, regression had only this biological meaning, but his work was later extended by Udny Yule and Karl Pearson to a more general statistical context.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In the work of Yule and Pearson, the joint distribution of the response and explanatory variables is assumed to be Gaussian.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Fisher assumed that the conditional distribution of the response variable is Gaussian, but the joint distribution need not be.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In this respect, Fisher's assumption is closer to Gauss's formulation of 1821.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In the 1950s and 1960s, economists used electromechanical desk calculators to calculate regressions.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Before 1970, it sometimes took up to 24 hours to receive the result from one regression.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Regression methods continue to be an area of active research.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Modern regression analysis is typically done with statistical and spreadsheet software packages on computers as well as on handheld scientific and graphing calculators.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In practice, researchers first select a model they would like to estimate and then use their chosen method (e.g., ordinary least squares) to estimate the parameters of that model.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In various fields of application, different terminologies are used in place of dependent and independent variables.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In the standard regression model, the independent variables $X_{i}$ are assumed to be free of error.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The errors-in-variables model can be used if the independent variables are assumed to contain errors.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Other modifications to the standard regression model can be made to account for various scenarios, such as situations involving omitted variables, confounding variables or endogeneity.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The researchers' goal is to estimate the function $f(X_{i},\beta )$ that most closely fits the data.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] To carry out regression analysis, the form of the function f must be specified.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Sometimes the form of this function is based on knowledge about the relationship between $Y_{i}$ and $X_{i}$ that does not rely on the data.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] If no such knowledge is available, a flexible or convenient form for f is chosen.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For example, a simple univariate regression may propose $f(X_{i},\beta )=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}$ , suggesting that the researcher believes $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{i}+e_{i}$ to be a reasonable approximation for the statistical process generating the data.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Once researchers determine their preferred statistical model, different forms of regression analysis provide tools to estimate the parameters $\beta$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For example, least squares (including its most common variant, ordinary least squares) finds the value of $\beta$ that minimizes the sum of squared errors $\sum _{i}(Y_{i}-f(X_{i},\beta ))^{2}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] A given regression method will ultimately provide an estimate of $\beta$ , usually denoted ${\hat {\beta }}$ to distinguish the estimate from the true (unknown) parameter value that generated the data.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Using this estimate, the researcher can then use the *fitted value* ${\hat {Y_{i}}}=f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ for prediction or to assess the accuracy of the model in explaining the data.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Whether the researcher is intrinsically interested in the estimate ${\hat {\beta }}$ or the predicted value ${\hat {Y_{i}}}$ will depend on context and their goals.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] As described in ordinary least squares, least squares is widely used because the estimated function $f(X_{i},{\hat {\beta }})$ approximates the conditional expectation $E(Y_{i}|X_{i})$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] However, alternative variants (e.g., least absolute deviations or quantile regression) are useful when researchers want to model other functions $f(X_{i},\beta )$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] There must be sufficient data to estimate a regression model.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For example, suppose that a researcher has access to N rows of data with one dependent and two independent variables: $(Y_{i},X_{1i},X_{2i})$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Suppose further that the researcher wants to estimate a bivariate linear model via least squares: $Y_{i}=\beta _{0}+\beta _{1}X_{1i}+\beta _{2}X_{2i}+e_{i}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] To understand why there are infinitely many options, note that the system of $N=2$ equations is to be solved for 3 unknowns, which makes the system underdetermined.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Alternatively, one can visualize infinitely many 3-dimensional planes that go through $N=2$ fixed points.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] More generally, to estimate a least squares model with k distinct parameters, one must have $N\geq k$ distinct data points.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] If $N>k$ , then there does not generally exist a set of parameters that will perfectly fit the data.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The quantity $N-k$ appears often in regression analysis, and is referred to as the degrees of freedom in the model.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Moreover, to estimate a least squares model, the independent variables $(X_{1i},X_{2i},...,X_{ki})$ must be linearly independent: one must *not* be able to reconstruct any of the independent variables by adding and multiplying the remaining independent variables.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] As discussed in ordinary least squares, this condition ensures that $X^{T}X$ is an invertible matrix and therefore that a unique solution ${\hat {\beta }}$ exists.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] By itself, a regression is just a computation performed on a set of data.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In order to interpret the resultant regression as a meaningful statistical model that quantifies real-world relationships, researchers often rely on a number of classical assumptions.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] A handful of conditions are sufficient for the least-squares estimator to possess desirable properties: in particular, the Gauss–Markov assumptions imply that the parameter estimates will be unbiased, consistent, and efficient in the class of linear unbiased estimators.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Practitioners have developed a variety of methods to maintain some or all of these desirable properties in real-world settings, because these classical assumptions are unlikely to hold exactly.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For example, modeling errors-in-variables can lead to reasonable estimates independent variables are measured with errors.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Heteroscedasticity-consistent standard errors allow the variance of $e_{i}$ to change across values of $X_{i}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Correlated errors that exist within subsets of the data or follow specific patterns can be handled using *clustered standard errors, geographic weighted regression*, or Newey–West standard errors, among other techniques.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] When rows of data correspond to locations in space, the choice of how to model $e_{i}$ within geographic units can have important consequences.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The subfield of econometrics is largely focused on developing techniques that allow researchers to make reasonable real-world conclusions in real-world settings, where classical assumptions do not hold exactly.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In linear regression, the model specification is that the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ is a linear combination of the *parameters* (but need not be linear in the *independent variables*).
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In multiple linear regression, there are several independent variables or functions of independent variables.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In both cases, $\varepsilon _{i}$ is an error term and the subscript i indexes a particular observation.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The residual, $e_{i}=y_{i}-{\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , is the difference between the value of the dependent variable predicted by the model, ${\widehat {y}}_{i}$ , and the true value of the dependent variable, $y_{i}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] One method of estimation is ordinary least squares.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Minimization of this function results in a set of normal equations, a set of simultaneous linear equations in the parameters, which are solved to yield the parameter estimators, ${\widehat {\beta }}_{0},{\widehat {\beta }}_{1}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] where ${\bar {x}}$ is the mean (average) of the x values and ${\bar {y}}$ is the mean of the y values.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] This is called the mean square error (MSE) of the regression.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The denominator is the sample size reduced by the number of model parameters estimated from the same data, $(n-p)$ for p regressors or $(n-p-1)$ if an intercept is used.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] In this case, $p=1$ so the denominator is $n-2$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Under the further assumption that the population error term is normally distributed, the researcher can use these estimated standard errors to create confidence intervals and conduct hypothesis tests about the population parameters.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] where $x_{ij}$ is the i -th observation on the j -th independent variable.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] If the first independent variable takes the value 1 for all i , $x_{i1}=1$ , then $\beta _{1}$ is called the regression intercept.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The least squares parameter estimates are obtained from p normal equations.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] where the $ij$ element of $\mathbf {X}$ is $x_{ij}$ , the i element of the column vector Y is $y_{i}$ , and the j element of ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}$ is ${\hat {\beta }}_{j}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Once a regression model has been constructed, it may be important to confirm the goodness of fit of the model and the statistical significance of the estimated parameters.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Commonly used checks of goodness of fit include the R-squared, analyses of the pattern of residuals and hypothesis testing.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Statistical significance can be checked by an F-test of the overall fit, followed by t-tests of individual parameters.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Interpretations of these diagnostic tests rest heavily on the model's assumptions.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Although examination of the residuals can be used to invalidate a model, the results of a t-test or F-test are sometimes more difficult to interpret if the model's assumptions are violated.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For example, if the error term does not have a normal distribution, in small samples the estimated parameters will not follow normal distributions and complicate inference.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] With relatively large samples, however, a central limit theorem can be invoked such that hypothesis testing may proceed using asymptotic approximations.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Limited dependent variables, which are response variables that are categorical or constrained to fall only in a certain range, often arise in econometrics.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The response variable may be non-continuous ("limited" to lie on some subset of the real line).
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For binary (zero or one) variables, if analysis proceeds with least-squares linear regression, the model is called the linear probability model.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Nonlinear models for binary dependent variables include the probit and logit model.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The multivariate probit model is a standard method of estimating a joint relationship between several binary dependent variables and some independent variables.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For categorical variables with more than two values there is the multinomial logit.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For ordinal variables with more than two values, there are the ordered logit and ordered probit models.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Censored regression models may be used when the dependent variable is only sometimes observed, and Heckman correction type models may be used when the sample is not randomly selected from the population of interest.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] An alternative to such procedures is linear regression based on polychoric correlation (or polyserial correlations) between the categorical variables.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Such procedures differ in the assumptions made about the distribution of the variables in the population.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] If the variable is positive with low values and represents the repetition of the occurrence of an event, then count models like the Poisson regression or the negative binomial model may be used.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] When the model function is not linear in the parameters, the sum of squares must be minimized by an iterative procedure.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] This introduces many complications which are summarized in Differences between linear and non-linear least squares.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Regression models ***predict*** a value of the *Y* variable given known values of the *X* variables.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Prediction *within* the range of values in the dataset used for model-fitting is known informally as *interpolation*.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Prediction *outside* this range of the data is known as *extrapolation*.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Performing extrapolation relies strongly on the regression assumptions.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The further the extrapolation goes outside the data, the more room there is for the model to fail due to differences between the assumptions and the sample data or the true values.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] A *prediction interval* that represents the uncertainty may accompany the point prediction.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Such intervals tend to expand rapidly as the values of the independent variable(s) moved outside the range covered by the observed data.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For such reasons and others, some tend to say that it might be unwise to undertake extrapolation.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The assumption of a particular form for the relation between *Y* and *X* is another source of uncertainty.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] A properly conducted regression analysis will include an assessment of how well the assumed form is matched by the observed data, but it can only do so within the range of values of the independent variables actually available.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] This means that any extrapolation is particularly reliant on the assumptions being made about the structural form of the regression relationship.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] If this knowledge includes the fact that the dependent variable cannot go outside a certain range of values, this can be made use of in selecting the model – even if the observed dataset has no values particularly near such bounds.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] The implications of this step of choosing an appropriate functional form for the regression can be great when extrapolation is considered.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] At a minimum, it can ensure that any extrapolation arising from a fitted model is "realistic" (or in accord with what is known).
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] There are no generally agreed methods for relating the number of observations versus the number of independent variables in the model.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] One method conjectured by Good and Hardin is $N=m^{n}$ , where N is the sample size, n is the number of independent variables and m is the number of observations needed to reach the desired precision if the model had only one independent variable.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] For example, a researcher is building a linear regression model using a dataset that contains 1000 patients ( N ).
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] All major statistical software packages perform least squares regression analysis and inference.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Simple linear regression and multiple regression using least squares can be done in some spreadsheet applications and on some calculators.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] While many statistical software packages can perform various types of nonparametric and robust regression, these methods are less standardized.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Different software packages implement different methods, and a method with a given name may be implemented differently in different packages.
[src:elastic-net/regression-analysis] Specialized regression software has been developed for use in fields such as survey analysis and neuroimaging.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The first comes up when the number of variables in the linear system exceeds the number of observations.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] In such settings, the ordinary least-squares problem is ill-posed and is therefore impossible to fit because the associated optimization problem has infinitely many solutions.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] RLS allows the introduction of further constraints that uniquely determine the solution.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The second reason for using RLS arises when the learned model suffers from poor generalization.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] RLS can be used in such cases to improve the generalizability of the model by constraining it at training time.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This constraint can either force the solution to be "sparse" in some way or to reflect other prior knowledge about the problem such as information about correlations between features.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] A Bayesian understanding of this can be reached by showing that RLS methods are often equivalent to priors on the solution to the least-squares problem.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Consider a learning setting given by a probabilistic space $(X\times Y,\rho (X,Y))$ , $Y\in R$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Let $S=\{x_{i},y_{i}\}_{i=1}^{n}$ denote a training set of n pairs i.i.d. with respect to the joint distribution $\rho$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Let $V:Y\times R\to [0;\infty )$ be a loss function.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Define F as the space of the functions such that expected risk: $\varepsilon (f)=\int V(y,f(x))\,d\rho (x,y)$ is well defined.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The main goal is to minimize the expected risk: $\inf _{f\in F}\varepsilon (f)$ Since the problem cannot be solved exactly there is a need to specify how to measure the quality of a solution.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] A good learning algorithm should provide an estimator with a small risk.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] As the joint distribution $\rho$ is typically unknown, the empirical risk is taken.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] However, if the functions are from a relatively unconstrained space, such as the set of square-integrable functions on X , this approach may overfit the training data, and lead to poor generalization.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Thus, it should somehow constrain or penalize the complexity of the function f .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] A RKHS can be defined by a symmetric positive-definite kernel function $K(x,z)$ with the reproducing property: $\langle K_{x},f\rangle _{\mathcal {H}}=f(x),$ where $K_{x}(z)=K(x,z)$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The RKHS for a kernel K consists of the completion of the space of functions spanned by $\left\{K_{x}\mid x\in X\right\}$ : ${\textstyle f(x)=\sum _{i=1}^{n}\alpha _{i}K_{x_{i}}(x),\,f\in {\mathcal {H}}}$ , where all $\alpha _{i}$ are real numbers.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Note that for an arbitrary loss function V , this approach defines a general class of algorithms named Tikhonov regularization.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] For instance, using the hinge loss leads to the support vector machine algorithm, and using the epsilon-insensitive loss leads to support vector regression.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The representer theorem guarantees that the solution can be written as: $f(x)=\sum _{i=1}^{n}c_{i}K(x_{i},x)$ for some $c\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The complexity of training is basically the cost of computing the kernel matrix plus the cost of solving the linear system which is roughly $O(n^{3})$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The computation of the kernel matrix for the linear or Gaussian kernel is $O(n^{2}D)$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] For convenience a vector notation is introduced.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Let X be an $n\times d$ matrix, where the rows are input vectors, and Y a $n\times 1$ vector where the entries are corresponding outputs.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] In terms of vectors, the kernel matrix can be written as $K=XX^{\mathsf {T}}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The first term is the objective function from ordinary least squares (OLS) regression, corresponding to the residual sum of squares.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The second term is a regularization term, not present in OLS, which penalizes large w values.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] As a smooth finite dimensional problem is considered and it is possible to apply standard calculus tools.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This solution closely resembles that of standard linear regression, with an extra term $\lambda I$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] If the assumptions of OLS regression hold, the solution $w=\left(X^{\mathsf {T}}X\right)^{-1}X^{\mathsf {T}}y$ , with $\lambda =0$ , is an unbiased estimator, and is the minimum-variance linear unbiased estimator, according to the Gauss–Markov theorem.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The term $\lambda nI$ therefore leads to a biased solution; however, it also tends to reduce variance.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This is easy to see, as the covariance matrix of the w -values is proportional to $\left(X^{\mathsf {T}}X+\lambda nI\right)^{-1}$ , and therefore large values of $\lambda$ will lead to lower variance.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Therefore, manipulating $\lambda$ corresponds to trading-off bias and variance.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] For problems with high-variance w estimates, such as cases with relatively small n or with correlated regressors, the optimal prediction accuracy may be obtained by using a nonzero $\lambda$ , and thus introducing some bias to reduce variance.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Furthermore, it is not uncommon in machine learning to have cases where $n<d$ , in which case $X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ is rank-deficient, and a nonzero $\lambda$ is necessary to compute $\left(X^{\mathsf {T}}X+\lambda nI\right)^{-1}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The parameter $\lambda$ controls the invertibility of the matrix $X^{\mathsf {T}}X+\lambda nI$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Several methods can be used to solve the above linear system, Cholesky decomposition being probably the method of choice, since the matrix $X^{\mathsf {T}}X+\lambda nI$ is symmetric and positive definite.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The complexity of this method is $O(nD^{2})$ for training and $O(D)$ for testing.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The cost $O(nD^{2})$ is essentially that of computing $X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ , whereas the inverse computation (or rather the solution of the linear system) is roughly $O(D^{3})$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] In this section it will be shown how to extend RLS to any kind of reproducing kernel K.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Instead of linear kernel a feature map is considered $\Phi :X\to F$ for some Hilbert space F , called the feature space.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This approach is known as the kernel trick.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This technique can significantly simplify the computational operations.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] If F is high dimensional, computing $\varphi (x_{i})$ may be rather intensive.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] If the explicit form of the kernel function is known, we just need to compute and store the $n\times n$ kernel matrix K .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] In fact, the Hilbert space F need not be isomorphic to $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ , and can be infinite dimensional.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This follows from Mercer's theorem, which states that a continuous, symmetric, positive definite kernel function can be expressed as $K(x,z)=\sum _{i=1}^{\infty }\sigma _{i}e_{i}(x)e_{i}(z)$ where $e_{i}(x)$ form an orthonormal basis for $\ell ^{2}(X)$ , and $\sigma _{i}\in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] If feature maps is defined $\varphi (x)$ with components $\varphi _{i}(x)={\sqrt {\sigma _{i}}}e_{i}(x)$ , it follows that $K(x,z)=\langle \varphi (x),\varphi (z)\rangle$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This demonstrates that any kernel can be associated with a feature map, and that RLS generally consists of linear RLS performed in some possibly higher-dimensional feature space.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] While Mercer's theorem shows how one feature map that can be associated with a kernel, in fact multiple feature maps can be associated with a given reproducing kernel.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] For instance, the map $\varphi (x)=K_{x}$ satisfies the property $K(x,z)=\langle \varphi (x),\varphi (z)\rangle$ for an arbitrary reproducing kernel.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Least squares can be viewed as a likelihood maximization under an assumption of normally distributed residuals.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This is because the exponent of the Gaussian distribution is quadratic in the data, and so is the least-squares objective function.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] In this framework, the regularization terms of RLS can be understood to be encoding priors on w .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] For instance, Tikhonov regularization corresponds to a normally distributed prior on w that is centered at 0.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] To see this, first note that the OLS objective is proportional to the log-likelihood function when each sampled $y^{i}$ is normally distributed around $w^{\mathsf {T}}\cdot x^{i}$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Then observe that a normal prior on w centered at 0 has a log-probability of the form $\log P(w)=q-\alpha \sum _{j=1}^{d}w_{j}^{2}$ where q and $\alpha$ are constants that depend on the variance of the prior and are independent of w .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Thus, minimizing the logarithm of the likelihood times the prior is equivalent to minimizing the sum of the OLS loss function and the ridge regression regularization term.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Other regularization methods correspond to different priors.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The following is a list of possible choices of the regularization function $R(\cdot )$ , along with the name for each one, the corresponding prior if there is a simple one, and ways for computing the solution to the resulting optimization problem.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] When $\lambda =0$ , i.e., in the case of ordinary least squares, the condition that $d>n$ causes the sample covariance matrix ${\frac {1}{n}}X^{\mathsf {T}}X$ to not have full rank and so it cannot be inverted to yield a unique solution.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This is why there can be an infinitude of solutions to the ordinary least squares problem when $d>n$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] However, when $\lambda >0$ , i.e., when ridge regression is used, the addition of $\lambda I$ to the sample covariance matrix ensures that all of its eigenvalues will be strictly greater than 0.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] In other words, it becomes invertible, and the solution is then unique.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Compared to ordinary least squares, ridge regression is not unbiased.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] It accepts bias to reduce variance and the mean square error.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This algorithm, for automatic (as opposed to heuristic) regularization, is obtained as a fixed point solution in the maximum likelihood estimation of the parameters.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Although the guarantees of convergence are not provided, the examples indicate that a satisfactory solution may be obtained after a couple of iterations.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Thus, while it can be used without problems for $n>d$ caution is recommended for $n<d$ .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] The least absolute selection and shrinkage (LASSO) method is another popular choice.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Note that the lasso penalty function is convex but not strictly convex.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Unlike Tikhonov regularization, this scheme does not have a convenient closed-form solution: instead, the solution is typically found using quadratic programming or more general convex optimization methods, as well as by specific algorithms such as the least-angle regression algorithm.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] An important difference between lasso regression and Tikhonov regularization is that lasso regression forces more entries of w to actually equal 0 than would otherwise.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] In contrast, while Tikhonov regularization forces entries of w to be small, it does not force more of them to be 0 than would be otherwise.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Thus, LASSO regularization is more appropriate than Tikhonov regularization in cases in which we expect the number of non-zero entries of w to be small, and Tikhonov regularization is more appropriate when we expect that entries of w will generally be small but not necessarily zero.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Which of these regimes is more relevant depends on the specific data set at hand.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Besides feature selection described above, LASSO has some limitations.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Ridge regression provides better accuracy in the case $n>d$ for highly correlated variables.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] In another case, $n<d$ , LASSO selects at most n variables.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Moreover, LASSO tends to select some arbitrary variables from group of highly correlated samples, so there is no grouping effect.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This corresponds to setting $R(w)$ to be the $\ell _{0}$ norm of w .
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] This regularization function, while attractive for the sparsity that it guarantees, is very difficult to solve because doing so requires optimization of a function that is not even weakly convex.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Lasso regression is the minimal possible relaxation of $\ell _{0}$ penalization that yields a weakly convex optimization problem.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] Consider $(1-\alpha )\left\|w\right\|_{1}+\alpha \left\|w\right\|_{2}\leq t$ as an Elastic Net penalty function.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] One of the main properties of the Elastic Net is that it can select groups of correlated variables.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] If $x_{i}$ and $x_{j}$ are highly correlated ( $\rho _{ij}\to 1$ ), the weight vectors are very close.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] In the case of negatively correlated samples ( $\rho _{ij}\to -1$ ) the samples $-x_{j}$ can be taken.
[src:elastic-net/regularized-least-squares] To summarize, for highly correlated variables the weight vectors tend to be equal up to a sign in the case of negative correlated variables.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] The theory was first introduced by Hoerl and Kennard in 1970 in their *Technometrics* papers "Ridge regressions: biased estimation of nonorthogonal problems" and "Ridge regressions: applications in nonorthogonal problems".
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Ridge regression was developed as a possible solution to the imprecision of least square estimators when linear regression models have some multicollinear (highly correlated) independent variables—by creating a ridge regression estimator (RR).
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] This provides a more precise ridge parameters estimate, as its variance and mean square estimator are often smaller than the least square estimators previously derived.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] the problem of a near-singular moment matrix $\mathbf {X} ^{\mathsf {T}}\mathbf {X}$ is alleviated by adding positive elements to the diagonals, thereby decreasing its condition number.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] In fact, there is a one-to-one relationship between c and $\lambda$ and since, in practice, we do not know c , we define $\lambda$ heuristically or find it via additional data-fitting strategies, see Determination of the Tikhonov parameter below.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] The optimal regularization parameter $\lambda$ is usually unknown and in practice needs to be estimated.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Typically, a data-driven choice for the Tikhonov regularization parameter $\lambda$ is accomplished either via cross-validation, or via a plug-in procedure, as follows.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] A common data-driven choice for $\lambda$ is the minimizer of the cross-validation loss or its generalizations.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Assume that $\mathbf {X}$ is an $n\times p$ matrix and define the matrix $\Omega :=(\mathbf {X} ^{\top }\mathbf {X} /n)^{+}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] where $\varsigma ^{2}$ is the variance of the noise ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}=\mathbf {Y} -\mathbf {X} {\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ , that is, $\mathrm {Var} ({\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }})=\varsigma ^{2}\mathbf {I}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] It can be shown that the ridge estimator ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}_{\lambda ^{*}}$ enjoys smaller expected in-sample risk than the minimum-norm least-squares estimator ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}_{0}=\mathbf {X} ^{+}\mathbf {Y}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] where the expectations treat $\mathbf {X}$ as fixed and $\mathbf {Y} '$ is *test response* data, independent from $\mathbf {Y}$ (and hence independent from the estimators ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}_{0}$ and ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}_{\lambda ^{*}}$ ).
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Of course, in practice the formula for $\lambda ^{*}$ is used by plugging in statistical estimators for the unknown parameters ${\boldsymbol {\beta }}$ and $\varsigma ^{2}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Alternative approaches to the data-driven selection of the Tikhonov regularization parameter include the discrepancy principle, L-curve method, restricted maximum likelihood.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Tikhonov regularization was invented independently in many different contexts.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] It became widely known through its application to integral equations in the works of Andrey Tikhonov and David L.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Some authors use the term **Tikhonov–Phillips regularization**.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] The finite-dimensional case was expounded by Arthur E.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Hoerl, who took a statistical approach, and by Manus Foster, who interpreted this method as a Wiener–Kolmogorov (Kriging) filter.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Following Hoerl, it is known in the statistical literature as ridge regression, named after ridge analysis ("ridge" refers to the path from the constrained maximum).
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Suppose that for a known real matrix A and vector $\mathbf {b}$ , we wish to find a vector $\mathbf {x}$ such that $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b} ,$ where $\mathbf {x}$ and $\mathbf {b}$ may be of different sizes and A may even be non-square.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] The standard approach is ordinary least squares linear regression.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] However, if no $\mathbf {x}$ satisfies the equation or more than one $\mathbf {x}$ does—that is, the solution is not unique—the problem is said to be ill posed.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] In such cases, ordinary least squares estimation leads to an overdetermined, or more often an underdetermined system of equations.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Most real-world phenomena have the effect of low-pass filters in the forward direction where A maps $\mathbf {x}$ to $\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Therefore, in solving the inverse-problem, the inverse mapping operates as a high-pass filter that has the undesirable tendency of amplifying noise (eigenvalues / singular values are largest in the reverse mapping where they were smallest in the forward mapping).
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] In addition, ordinary least squares implicitly nullifies every element of the reconstructed version of $\mathbf {x}$ that is in the null-space of A , rather than allowing for a model to be used as a prior for $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Ordinary least squares seeks to minimize the sum of squared residuals, which can be compactly written as $\left\|A\mathbf {x} -\mathbf {b} \right\|_{2}^{2},$ where $\|\cdot \|_{2}$ is the Euclidean norm.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] In many cases, this matrix is chosen as a scalar multiple of the identity matrix ( $\Gamma =\alpha I$ ), giving preference to solutions with smaller norms; this is known as ***L*2 regularization**.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] In other cases, high-pass operators (e.g., a difference operator or a weighted Fourier operator) may be used to enforce smoothness if the underlying vector is believed to be mostly continuous.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] This regularization improves the conditioning of the problem, thus enabling a direct numerical solution.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] For $\Gamma =0$ this reduces to the unregularized least-squares solution, provided that (*A*T*A*)−1 exists.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Note that in case of a complex matrix A , as usual the transpose $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ has to be replaced by the Hermitian transpose $A^{\mathsf {H}}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Since Tikhonov Regularization simply adds a quadratic term to the objective function in optimization problems, it is possible to do so after the unregularised optimisation has taken place.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] In the context of arbitrary likelihood fits, this is valid, as long as the quadratic approximation of the likelihood function is valid.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] This means that, as long as the perturbation from the unregularised result is small, one can regularise any result that is presented as a best fit point with a covariance matrix.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] No detailed knowledge of the underlying likelihood function is needed.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] For general multivariate normal distributions for $\mathbf {x}$ and the data error, one can apply a transformation of the variables to reduce to the case above.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] In the Bayesian interpretation P is the inverse covariance matrix of $\mathbf {b}$ , $\mathbf {x} _{0}$ is the expected value of $\mathbf {x}$ , and Q is the inverse covariance matrix of $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] The Tikhonov matrix is not explicitly included because the corresponding regularization term $\left\|\Gamma \mathbf {x} -\mathbf {x} _{0}'\right\|_{Q'}^{2}$ reduces to above with $\Gamma \mathbf {x} _{0}=\mathbf {x} _{0}'$ and $Q=\Gamma ^{T}Q'\Gamma$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] For normal regularization where $Q'=I$ , the Tikhonov matrix then appears in the Cholesky factorization $Q=\Gamma ^{\mathsf {T}}\Gamma$ and is considered a whitening filter.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] In some situations, one can avoid using the transpose $A^{\mathsf {T}}$ , as proposed by Mikhail Lavrentyev.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Typically discrete linear ill-conditioned problems result from discretization of integral equations, and one can formulate a Tikhonov regularization in the original infinite-dimensional context.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] In the above we can interpret A as a compact operator on Hilbert spaces, and x and b as elements in the domain and range of A .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] The operator $A^{*}A+\Gamma ^{\mathsf {T}}\Gamma$ is then a self-adjoint bounded invertible operator.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] With $\Gamma =\alpha I$ , this least-squares solution can be analyzed in a special way using the singular-value decomposition.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] This demonstrates the effect of the Tikhonov parameter on the condition number of the regularized problem.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] For the generalized case, a similar representation can be derived using a generalized singular-value decomposition.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] The probabilistic formulation of an inverse problem introduces (when all uncertainties are Gaussian) a covariance matrix $C_{M}$ representing the *a priori* uncertainties on the model parameters, and a covariance matrix $C_{D}$ representing the uncertainties on the observed parameters.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] In the special case when these two matrices are diagonal and isotropic, $C_{M}=\sigma _{M}^{2}I$ and $C_{D}=\sigma _{D}^{2}I$ , and, in this case, the equations of inverse theory reduce to the equations above, with $\alpha ={\sigma _{D}}/{\sigma _{M}}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Although at first the choice of the solution to this regularized problem may look artificial, and indeed the matrix $\Gamma$ seems rather arbitrary, the process can be justified from a Bayesian point of view.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Note that for an ill-posed problem one must necessarily introduce some additional assumptions in order to get a unique solution.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Statistically, the prior probability distribution of x is sometimes taken to be a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] For simplicity here, the following assumptions are made: the means are zero; their components are independent; the components have the same standard deviation $\sigma _{x}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] The data are also subject to errors, and the errors in b are also assumed to be independent with zero mean and standard deviation $\sigma _{b}$ .
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] Under these assumptions the Tikhonov-regularized solution is the most probable solution given the data and the *a priori* distribution of x , according to Bayes' theorem.
[src:elastic-net/tikhonov-regularization] If the assumption of normality is replaced by assumptions of homoscedasticity and uncorrelatedness of errors, and if one still assumes zero mean, then the Gauss–Markov theorem entails that the solution is the minimal unbiased linear estimator.
